children.name: Text

children.name: Text
children.value: I reach out to all ship's captains, adventurers, luminaries, and merchant traders the length and breadth of the Empire! Heed my call! The life of many a good sailor is on the line.

children.name: Text
children.value: It has been three years since the Arctic Council sent its two best ships in search of the legendary north-west passage, led by my dear husband, Sir John Faithful.

children.name: Text
children.value: We've not heard from them since. The Arctic Council are sending rescue parties north, but their fleet is too thin to cover that vast territory before the arctic winter kicks in.

children.name: Text
children.value: Are you decent and courageous enough to join this sole woman's cause? Worry not! Your combined efforts will be generously recompensed!

children.name: Text
children.value: Can it be, the Arctic Council retreating just as we arrive? I mean the chairman is nonetheless correct, the pack ice grows stronger every day. Still, I have no intention of giving up as they have done.

children.name: Text
children.value: I have assembled many of the finest-known craftsmen and ship-builders at our outpost. Presently they are preparing the shipyards to house our impressive icebreakers— vessels that will help carve a way through this frozen world.

children.name: Text
children.value: I know it is a lot to ask, but will you endure and help me to create the fleet we need?

children.name: Text
children.value: And have we gone too far also, my friend?

children.name: Text
children.value: Then let us be swift and brave. If only I knew what awaited us upon this eternal expanse.

children.name: Text
children.value: Finally all those sailors may rejoice with their loved ones. I know what you are thinking. But don't worry. I feel no bitterness.

children.name: Text
children.value: I know the rest are alive out there, and Sir John's broad shoulders shelter them from wind and snow.

children.name: Text
children.value: All the stories being shared about my husband give me the strength to return next summer, with an even bigger fleet. Can I count on you again then? I dare hope so, my friend! I dare hope.

children.name: Text
children.value: Let's not beat around the bush! We found nothing but endless white, not a single soul saved.

children.name: Text
children.value: And yet I know that my husband and his men are out there somewhere. Frozen cold, but alive! Still alive.

children.name: Text
children.value: I will fund another rescue attempt, come back next year, better-prepared, with more ships and even-more-determined allies. Will you sail beside me again then? I dare to hope, my friend. I dare to hope!

children.name: Text

children.name: Text

children.name: Text

children.name: Text

children.name: Text

children.name: Text
children.value: Please, don't follow the Arctic Council's example.

children.name: Text
children.value: Perhaps you don't realise the scale of this undertaking.

children.name: Text
children.value: You don't seem as committed as the others.

children.name: Text
children.value: I, Lady Faithful, knock at every door to rouse the bold and the daring.

children.name: Text
children.value: You may know of my husband, Sir John Faithful whose Arctic expedition is lost and forsaken?

children.name: Text
children.value: Be assured, your efforts will be suitably rewarded.

children.name: Text
children.value: We must stick together if we are to endure the chill.

children.name: Text
children.value: It cannot be long now before we find something.

children.name: Text
children.value: The absence of a base camp might explain why the Arctic council never sustained their rescue efforts.

children.name: Text
children.value: This encampment must embody hope, our one comfort in the wilderness.

children.name: Text
children.value: Until the fate of any lost ship is affirmed, our efforts should not diminish.

children.name: Text
children.value: Many ships from many sponsors, united by a profound desire to bring back those men alive.

children.name: Text
children.value: Just when I was beginning to lose faith.

children.name: Text
children.value: If we pull together like this, who knows what we can achieve.

children.name: Text
children.value: We must thank the Inuit spirits who dwell here.

children.name: Text
children.value: Yes, we must set our preconceptions aside.

children.name: Text
children.value: It would only make me worry.

children.name: Text
children.value: We must rally together now, if we are to find them.

children.name: Text
children.value: I value any help I can get, from any direction.

children.name: Text
children.value: You will be rewarded, I promise.

children.name: Text
children.value: Good, we all are with you.

children.name: Text
children.value: They said it was impossible, you proved them wrong!

children.name: Text
children.value: Was the reward not substantial enough?

children.name: Text
children.value: What could have led you astray?

children.name: Text
children.value: Seems we've not learned from the mistakes of the past.

children.name: Text
children.value: The cold has got to us.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Arctic summer is only a brief window.

children.name: Text
children.value: It does not end there, we must keep going.

children.name: Text
children.value: This must be a sustained effort.

children.name: Text
children.value: I know it feels like going from one pole to another.

children.name: Text
children.value: You made a seal hole, now catch a seal!

children.name: Text
children.value: I await news of our next compass heading.

children.name: Text
children.value: The matter is out of our hands for the time being.

children.name: Text
children.value: Who we have here?! Samuel Goode's child. Want to go down with your father, do you!

children.name: Text
children.value: You're too late. I was just a spark, and the touch-paper is already lit...

children.name: Text
children.value: They will come for you, for everybody!

children.name: Text
children.value: Want to go down with your father, do you!

children.name: Text
children.value: The sixth age of man approaches!

children.name: Text
children.value: We mortals shall take back the earth!

children.name: Text
children.value: When a limb is severed, a new one grows.

children.name: Text
children.value: This kingdom shall fall with the dawns's first rays!

children.name: Text
children.value: Drones build the nest. The Queen shall come.

children.name: Text
children.value: The head of Empire must come off.

children.name: Text
children.value: Interfere with our thralls at your peril!

children.name: Text
children.value: We only kept them alive to do our bidding.

children.name: Text
children.value: The thralls will serve our master.

children.name: Text
children.value: Isabel and her allies have trangressed for the last time! Die well!

children.name: Text
children.value: Now we must inflict what we might have saved for later.

children.name: Text
children.value: Isabel has forgotten what we do to those who disobey.

children.name: Text
children.value: Fire prolongs the agony of death!

children.name: Text
children.value: You know not with whom you meddle. Leave, if you value your life, else all shall burn.

children.name: Text
children.value: The earth must burn before it turns.

children.name: Text
children.value: The wheels turn and nothing can stop them.

children.name: Text
children.value: All must bow to the flames.

children.name: Text
children.value: For each head torn another grows back!

children.name: Text
children.value: You said we could not fail master!

children.name: Text
children.value: What of your promises master? What of our victory?

children.name: Text
children.value: When one is torn away another succeeds.

children.name: Text
children.value: There was a chance while yer father still lived, no use dragging it out now he's gone…

children.name: Text
children.value: Bright Sands will never be matched, if that's what you're set on.

children.name: Text
children.value: You are trying at least. I know Samuel wouldn't have given up.

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm starting to wonder if you can't turn things around.

children.name: Text
children.value: You can't bring back your father, but his spirit…

children.name: Text
children.value: I don't know what you're trying to achieve here, but it won't bring Samuel back.

children.name: Text
children.value: Mining for you, mining for Eli , what's the difference?

children.name: Text
children.value: Your father had that same steely look.

children.name: Text
children.value: It's no Bright Sands, but it really is something!

children.name: Text
children.value: Your company is flourishing. You may even be the match of your father - rest his soul.

children.name: Text
children.value: Samuel Goode’s engineer? Aye, that’s me. Who’s asking?

children.name: Text
children.value: So I'm a commodity now, to be bought and sold? Your father treated me like a human being.

children.name: Text
children.value: You're stubborn, that's for sure. A chip off the old block.

children.name: Text
children.value: So you're the one that fled his duties. Well you're too late, there's nothing to be done.

children.name: Text
children.value: You realise this will be no palm-tree paradise, only hard graft?

children.name: Text
children.value: My wife tells me I shouldn't be so hard on you.

children.name: Text
children.value: You're brave coming back, many people blame this all on you.

children.name: Text
children.value: Samuel always had high hopes for you. It was a great blow to him when you left.

children.name: Text
children.value: My prison outfit remains in protest.

children.name: Text
children.value: Edvard is the major cause of my distemper, not you.

children.name: Text
children.value: Somehow got used to these pyjama stripes.

children.name: Text
children.value: Dead or alive, I’ll always be Samuel’s man.

children.name: Text
children.value: I realise I should have told you sooner.

children.name: Text
children.value: Perhaps now you have the means to take justice into your own hands.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ah the prodigal child. Epitome of selfishness.

children.name: Text
children.value: It'll take a lot to convince me you're worthy of the name Goode.

children.name: Text
children.value: You never know what you have til it's gone, eh?

children.name: Text
children.value: Give me a reason to forgive you.

children.name: Text
children.value: I had believed it would only do harm to tell you, but I have grounds to believe your father was murdered.

children.name: Text
children.value: And the killer - his cellmate - walks free! The rumour is he's in hiding, preparing to flee to the New World.

children.name: Text
children.value: It is believed his accomplice supplies him with goods from the Emporium Exotique!

children.name: Text
children.value: Theodora! Finally I can hold you in my arms again!

children.name: Text
children.value: A shame you can't appreciate the craft this requires. Never mind, the charges have been primed, the perimeter cleared, we are ready to detonate.

children.name: Text
children.value: Praise checksum nine! Today is Anno day!

children.name: Text
children.value: ANNO 1800 wishes you a happy new year.

children.name: Text
children.value: Time flies! It's been ten hours! And there is no time-based achievement to await you, honestly.

children.name: Text
children.value: Twelve hours. Seriously? Turn the machine off this minute!

children.name: Text
children.value: Twenty-four hours and the game is still running. You've reached the end of line. No more play time warnings. Let's hope you pressed fast forward and left for bed, so I am merely talking to myself right now.

children.value: After the picket protests, many fine men left Bright Sands to join you.

children.name: Text
children.value: Then Edvard struck back! He imprisoned all who were close to your father, including my beloved Thomas.

children.name: Text
children.value: My husband and the others were deported to Wormways Prison and I've heard nothing from him ever since. If you do find him unharmed, prithee tell him his wife yearns for his return.

children.name: Text
children.value: Can't thank you enough for bailing my Thomas out of gaol.

children.name: Text
children.value: Not just my husband – all from your father’s circles were clapped in irons.

children.name: Text
children.value: I can be reunited with dear Mr. Ticker!

children.name: Text
children.value: We are, all of us, quite moved by your selfless actions. Your father would be proud.

children.name: Text
children.value: Saved! Do you also then save us from a grievous injustice…?

children.name: Text
children.value: Edvard’s charges against us are pure fabrication! The man is an impostor!

children.name: Text
children.value: I know we look like criminals, but we were trusted associates of your father.

children.name: Text
children.value: I bring grave news from our ice pilots. The pack ice becomes too thick. We'd be risking our ships if we were to continue our rescue.

children.name: Text
children.value: So with a heavy heart, I have ordered the Arctic council fleet to return southwards to our winter haven. But do not lose hope! We will gather ourselves and return next year.

children.name: Text
children.value: Enough of your grovelling! Rise Mortals! / Now, which role do you see for me in your little drama?

children.name: Text
children.value: Your attempts at flattery are futile. I am going to pwn a game of 1404 now. When I get back this will be “checksum=9: the musical” or you will feel my holy wrath.

children.name: Text
children.value: The moral of the story is simple. Without me, it doesn’t work. See you in Anno 1305!

children.name: Text
children.value: What should I be?! Say it! What is it this time? Should I hang lower in the sky? Should I turn with you? If I ever make it into the game without one person complaining I’ll eat my hat. Come on then you bright sparks, gift me an entry in the options menu, this wheelie-bin for half-finished features. Or even better! How about a day-night cycle, huh? Then every five minutes I can cede my throne to a rotten cheese!

children.name: Text
children.value: Peeps, in the old days nobody needed that. The world was in 2D. Everybody was happy that they could see anything at all.

children.name: Text
children.value: Edvard Goode. Are you ready to be reunited with your brother?

children.name: Text
children.value: Of course you are. The heat will peel your sins from your flesh like cloth. Acolytes, purge the place!

children.name: Text
children.value: Pathetic! But then, surely Samuel awaits you too! The whole Goode family can be reunited in the everlasting. We squeezed the life from your father's lungs, peeled your uncle's skin...You must be curious as to what we plan for you!

children.name: Text
children.value: A new world order is at stake— the Empire already shaking to its foundations, and the Goode family helpless to prevent it! We first eradicate the offspring and then eradicate the Queen!

children.name: Text
children.value: First Samuel, now Edvard! Soon I will be rid of your dreary family once and for all.

children.name: Text
children.value: Goode & Sons. Favourites of the Royal Council. How I've enjoyed watching your family's slow and ignoble demise.

children.name: Text
children.value: What a fool Edvard was to trust us!

children.name: Text

children.name: Text

children.name: Text

children.name: Text

children.name: Text

children.name: Text
